body:
The protected buckets are sometimes referred to as headers. 

> The IV can be placed in the unprotected header
> The Parital IV can be placed in the unprotected header
> The parameter is used to indicate which protected header labels
> This attribute is then encoded as an unprotected header.
> Applications SHOULD verify that the same label does not occur in both the protected and unprotected headers

> Headers = (
>     protected : empty_or_serialized_map,
>     unprotected : header_map
> )

title: "header", "parameter" or "header parameter"
body:
Is a kid, iv, content type... a "header", a "parameter" or a "header parameter"?

The textual description of each refers to them as "parameters" -- "This parameter is used to indicate..."

The summarizing table 2 calls them "header parameters". 

The paragraph on CDDL and the CDDL refers them as "headers".

I was theorizing that protected and unprotected are headers and kid, iv... are parameters or header parameters, but that isn't consistent with the text.

No ambiguity when implementing, but a little confusing to read.

If the official name is "header parameter" and "parameter" is the short name, then the main divergence is the CDDL and CDDL-related text. If the CDDL and CDDL-related text where changed to  use "header parameter" it seems like all would be consistent.

title: Fixing up quirks in XML
body:
There are a couple of quirks within the XML that might be causing some upstream errors:

* ` ` is not a well-known XML entity nor is it defined.
  - this switches to simply ' '
* `US-ASCII` is not widely supported by XML parsers/applications (there's a smorgasbord of history)
  - switched to 'UTF-8', which better aligns with RFC Editors' future plans
